  "titleEn": "Sentence Modifiers (Nawasikh)",
  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Exception Constructions (الاستثناء)",
      "titleArabic": "الاستثناء",
      "content": [
        "Exception (istithnā') constructs include a general statement, an exception particle (usually إِلَّا), and the excepted noun. Different types have different grammatical rules."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Muttaṣil: excepted is from the same category as the general",
        "Munqaṭi': excepted is from different category",
        "Mufarragh: general statement is negative/question",
        "إِلَّا, غَيْر, سِوَى are exception tools"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "جَاءَ الطُّلَّابُ إِلَّا زَيْدًا", "english": "The students came except Zaid" },
        { "arabic": "مَا جَاءَ إِلَّا زَيْدٌ", "english": "Only Zaid came (mufarragh)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Sentence Modifiers (النواسخ)",
      "titleArabic": "النواسخ",
      "content": [
        "Nawāsikh are particles and verbs that enter upon nominal sentences and change the grammatical case of mubtada' and khabar. They include kāna and its sisters, and inna and its sisters."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Kāna: ism remains raf', khabar becomes naṣb",
        "Inna: ism becomes naṣb, khabar remains raf'",
        "Sisters of kāna: أَصْبَحَ, أَمْسَى, صَارَ, ظَلَّ, لَيْسَ",
        "Sisters of inna: إِنَّ, أَنَّ, لَكِنَّ, لَيْتَ, لَعَلَّ, كَأَنَّ"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كَانَ الطَّالِبُ مُجْتَهِدًا", "english": "The student was diligent (kāna)" },
        { "arabic": "إِنَّ الْحَقَّ وَاضِحٌ", "english": "Indeed the truth is clear (inna)" }
      ]
    }
  ],
